<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-07-08T11:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-07-08T11:00:00-05:00" n="81" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d81">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">862.34/172: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Bingham</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-07-08T17:00:00+01:00">July 8,
                                    1935—5 p.m.</date>
                                <lb/> [Received July 8—12:07 p.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>304. The Sunday <hi rend="italic">Times</hi> carries a story without date
                            or place of origin to the effect that details of the German program of
                            naval construction have been communicated by the Germans themselves
                            direct to France and the other signatories to the Washington and London
                            naval treaties. It would be helpful in my conversation tomorrow with Sir
                            Samuel Hoare<note n="30" xml:id="d81fn30">British Secretary of State for
                                Foreign Affairs, June 7–Deeember 18, 1935.</note> if I could know
                            authoritatively whether the United States Government has received this
                            information from Germany.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Bingham</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>